<subSubSection id="C34F65339926447607D2FBD57BEBFB63" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BEA36B89926447607D2FBD57BEBFB63" blockId="31.[151,1437,1044,1395]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="B921EAAA9926447607D2FBD57947FBAE" bold="true" box="[151,597,1044,1071]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Diagnosis (extracted from literature).</emphasis>
Female. Length 
<quantity id="4CAD9B5D992644760451FBD5787FFBAE" box="[788,877,1044,1071]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" unit="mm" value="4.8">4.8 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis id="B921EAAA99264476043DFBD578D3FBAE" bold="true" box="[888,961,1044,1071]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Color.</emphasis>
Body castaneous. Mandible with two apical teeth, apical tooth much larger then inner one. Clypeus sharply elevated medially. Eye small, oval. Malar space short. Frons aciculate, punctures small and sparse. Head elongate with sides subparallel, vertex slightly weakly concave, 1/4 × longer than wide. Pronotum 1/2 × longer than wide; neck visible from above disc with sides parallel, anterior margin with median emargination. Mesotibia strongly spinose. Metasoma as long as head and mesosoma together.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C34F6533992644760782FB2D7AEAFACF" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BEA36B8992644760782FB2D7AEAFACF" blockId="31.[151,1437,1044,1395]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="B921EAAA992644760782FB2D7A5DFA86" bold="true" box="[199,335,1260,1287]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Comments.</emphasis>
We were not able to examine the 
<typeStatus id="54EE881A992644760597FB2C7810FA86" box="[722,770,1261,1287]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">type</typeStatus>
(MCZH). This diagnosis was obtained from 
<bibRefCitation id="EFC44B49992644760244FB2C7E8BFA87" author="Brues, C. T." box="[1281,1433,1260,1287]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="97 - 125" refId="ref49248" refString="Brues, C. T. (1918) Parasitic Hymenoptera from the British Solomon Islands collected by Dr. W. M. Mann. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 62, 97 - 125." type="journal article" year="1918">Brues (1918)</bibRefCitation>
. According to him, 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D3B99264476062CFAD0791AFAAB" authorityName="Brues" authorityYear="1918" box="[361,520,1296,1323]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="malaitensis">
<emphasis id="B921EAAA99264476062CFAD0791AFAAB" box="[361,520,1296,1323]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">A. malaitensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C554D3B9926447605DDFAD07800FAAB" authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1904" box="[664,786,1297,1323]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="proxima">
<emphasis id="B921EAAA9926447605DDFAD07800FAAB" box="[664,786,1297,1323]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">A. proxima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in color but the former has the head elongate, whereas the latter has the head subquadrate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
